{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nTHE security-critical divergence. e165 (change 563, commit 2efdae38f) implemented key\nvalidity as an **HLC-epoch** window (ordinal position in the reducer's canonical replay).\nThe APPROVED epic design requires **git-commit-ancestry** validity (tickets-branch commit\nSHAs). HLC ordering is partly author-assigned, so a malicious clone holding a\nlater-revoked key can write an event with a backdated HLC that sorts BEFORE the revocation\nand verifies as valid тАФ defeating the feature's core \"not attacker-controllable\" promise.\nThe immutable commit DAG closes that hole. This story transitions the delivered HLC-epoch\nmodel to the approved commit-ancestry model. (User rejected the delivered design; see\nsession_log d7c0.)\n\n## Why the DAG is stronger (record the rationale)\nCommit SHAs chain content+parents, so an event's position in history is a tamper-proof\nfact тАФ you cannot make a new event an ancestor of an existing revocation commit without\nforging SHAs. HLC ordering trusts the author-assigned timestamp component; commit ancestry\ntrusts only the DAG.\n\n## Architecture decision тАФ pure reducer + git-aware resolver (READ FIRST)\nThe reducer (`reduce_ticket` / `_processors.py`) is deliberately **pure-filesystem** today\n(no git, no subprocess) and MUST stay so тАФ its output is cache-keyed and it runs on plain\nevent-file directories. Commit SHAs are git metadata not present in event JSON, so we do\nNOT store SHAs in reduced state. Instead:\n\n- **Reducer keyring fold (pure):** records each key's lifecycle by **event position** (the\n  `{HLC-ts}-{uuid}` filename prefix the reducer already knows) тАФ record shape\n  `{public_key, added_at: <position>, revoked_at: <position|None>}`. Drop `added_epoch` /\n  `revoked_epoch` / `keyring_epoch` entirely. `state[\"keys\"]` = keys with `revoked_at is\n  None` (currently-valid).\n- **Git-aware resolver (new, in `authorship.py`):** a resolver maps a **position тЖТ\n  the tickets-branch commit SHA that introduced that event file** (`git log\n  --diff-filter=A --format=%H -- <ticketdir>/<position>-<TYPE>.json`, run in the tracker\n  dir), and `verify_authorship_at_commit(envelope, identity_id, event_commit, *,\n  repo_root)` builds the trust root from exactly the keys whose **added-commit is an\n  ancestor of `event_commit` AND whose revoked-commit (if any) is NOT** тАФ via `git\n  merge-base --is-ancestor`. This is where the AC's commit-anchored record\n  `{pubkey, added_at_commit, revoked_at_commit}` materializes (the resolver's output,\n  resolved from the reducer's position records); a test asserts that resolved shape using\n  two real fixture commits.\n- **Intra-commit refinement (N-events-per-commit):** `batch_stage_and_commit` puts N event\n  files in ONE commit, and `merge-base --is-ancestor(C, C)` is true, so when a key's\n  add/revoke shares the event's commit the DAG cannot order them тАФ refine with the\n  **intra-commit HLC position** (the `{ts}-{uuid}` prefix ordering within that commit):\n  added-in-same-commit counts as valid iff the KEY_ADD position тЙд the event position;\n  revoked-in-same-commit invalidates iff the KEY_REVOKE position тЙд the event position.\n\n## What\nReplace the epoch-based keyring with the commit-anchored model above:\n- Reducer `process_key_event` folds position-based records (no epoch); `make_initial_state`\n  seeds `keyring: []` (no `keyring_epoch`); snapshot freeze/restore carries the\n  position-based keyring (no epoch counter); genesis/TOFU bootstrap seeds static `keys`\n  with `added_at` = the CREATE position (or a genesis sentinel). Bump `SCHEMA_VERSION`\n  (v4тЖТv5) and `_REDUCER_CACHE_VERSION` (v5тЖТv6), both preserve-and-ignore for older clones.\n- `authorship.py`: add `verify_authorship_at_commit` + the positionтЖТcommit resolver +\n  commit-ancestry trust root; **REMOVE `verify_authorship_at_epoch`, `epoch_for_position`,\n  `keys_valid_at_epoch`** (the HLC-epoch API).\n- `identity.py` key add/revoke seam unchanged in shape (TOFU genesis self-signed; unsigned\n  non-genesis refused; signed add/rotate/revoke), still emitting KEY_ADD/KEY_REVOKE events.\n- Consumes TS1's in-toto authorship (verify the event's Statement against the identity's\n  keys valid at the event's commit).\n\n## Stack scoping (why TS2 and TS3 land together)\nThis story AMENDS Gerrit change 563 = commit 2efdae38f (e165), which touches ONLY\n`authorship.py`, `reducer/{_processors,_state,_version,_cache}.py`, and `identity.py`. The\n**consumers** of the era model тАФ `verify_authorship.py` (`_verify_signed` тЖТ epoch) and\n`compact.py` (ledger `epoch`) тАФ live in commit 721702e91 (3183), so they are rewired to\n`verify_authorship_at_commit` in **TS3 (117b, change 580)**. Because TS2 removes the epoch\nAPI from `authorship.py` while TS3 updates its commit-7 consumers, the two must be pushed\ntogether; each is internally green at its own patchset (at commit 563 the verify-gate does\nnot yet exist), and the full stack is green only once both are folded. TS2 reworks e165's\nOWN tests (`test_identity_e165*`) from epoch to commit-ancestry.\n\n## Scope\nIn: commit-anchored position-based key records, the positionтЖТcommit resolver, DAG-ancestry\nvalidity (`verify_authorship_at_commit`) with intra-commit refinement, TOFU/write-gate,\nreducer fold + snapshot + version bumps, and removal of the epoch API. Out: authorship\npayload format (TS1); the SNAPSHOT ledger schema + `key_not_valid_at_era` verdict + the\nverify-gate/compact rewiring (TS3 / 3183, commit 7).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] The resolved key record binds `{pubkey, added_at_commit, revoked_at_commit?}`\n  (tickets-branch commit SHAs); a test using TWO real fixture commits on the tickets branch\n  asserts the resolved record shape.\n- [ ] Genesis key-add is accepted ONLY when self-signed (TOFU base case); an unsigned\n  NON-genesis key-add is refused (test).\n- [ ] An event whose commit is NOT a descendant of the key's `added_at_commit` (or IS a\n  descendant of its `revoked_at_commit`) FAILS verification; one that IS a descendant of\n  `added_at_commit` and NOT of `revoked_at_commit` PASSES (test with two fixture commits,\n  both sides of the boundary).\n- [ ] Validity derives from commit ancestry, NOT event timestamps: an event with a\n  backdated `data` timestamp still verifies against the commit that actually introduced it\n  (test proves the timestamp does not change the governing commit).\n- [ ] Replay never rejects: a bad-signature / not-yet-valid-key event still folds into\n  state (test); the delivered HLC-epoch surface (`verify_authorship_at_epoch`,\n  `epoch_for_position`, `keys_valid_at_epoch`, `keyring_epoch`) is gone (grep-asserted\n  absent from src/rebar).\n- [ ] The reducer stays pure (no git/subprocess in `src/rebar/reducer/`); a grep-assert\n  confirms the reducer does not import subprocess/run git (the resolver lives in\n  `authorship.py`).\n\n## file_impact\n- `src/rebar/attest/authorship.py` (verify_authorship_at_commit + positionтЖТcommit resolver + commit-ancestry trust root; remove the epoch API)\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_processors.py` (position-based keyring fold; remove epoch counter + keys_valid_at_epoch)\n- `src/rebar/reducer/_state.py` + `_version.py` + `_cache.py` (position-based keyring seed + SCHEMA_VERSION v5 + cache v6)\n- `src/rebar/_commands/identity.py` (add/revoke key seam; TOFU genesis vs signed non-genesis unchanged in shape)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783883993577907001,"uuid":"02026931-5fb2-4def-a17c-381435502c87"}